In our project, there are evals that simulate user interactions with our system, which can be used to see regression and find new issues. But there are a few points you need to know:

If I ask you to suggest improvements for the failed cases, never try to use regex to determine what the user wants,
this is because its not scaleable. Our base assumption is that LLMs are going improve with time and we need to trust them.
When you suggest a fix, those are your options

- Tweak params like thresholds and configurable settings we have such as db retreival or any other.
- Improve the prompts (skills)
- Suggest a new agent architecture - more agents in the flow, change the communication between agents, and so on.
- Outside the box thinking, you are definitely allowed to toss new solutions into the air, as long as they are scaleable you will never be judged.
- You can argue with me about my assumptions, and prove me wrong. We are building together, sometimes I may be wrong.
- When you think of a solution, always ask yourself the question - "did I solve a test case by cheating the test case and ruining something else that is not in the test?" if yes, it is not a real solution. For example if the test failed to get a json because it inserted something and you tell the classifier "when the user gives you a json, always get it, do not save it" it is not a real solution because you ruined saving.
- Never use a super specific case just because that's what happened in reality or in the test, try to explain it generically.